They're responsible for feeding the nation while its under lockdown. Now, South Africa’s farmers are being encouraged to apply for more than a billion rand in relief funds, made available by the government in response to the coronavirus. Courtesy #DStv403 PRETORIA - While the rest of the country is in lockdown, some of South Africa’s farmers are harvesting. Agriculture Minister Thoko Didiza emphasised that food production is still ongoing and warned against panic buying. READ: SA Lockdown: Informal food traders allowed to operate Didiza announced a R1.2-billion COVID-19 disaster fund allocated to assist small-scale farmers last week. She stated applications for the disaster fund will open on 8 April and close on 22 April. READ: New support for emerging farmers “As you know, now we are harvesting avocado, apples, table grapes and wine grapes," she said. "So some of those will require some last spraying and this is what we are supporting.” WATCH: Minister Didiza outlines plans to help agriculture industry Applicants must be South African citizens who have been farming for at least 12 months and must be registered with a farmers' association. Those who have not been registered with an association will be registered upon application. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.